WEBVTT

00:00.034 --> 00:04.482
The following message by Alistair Begg is made available by Truth For Life.

00:04.502 --> 00:08.469
For more information, visit us online at truthforlife.org.

00:09.772 --> 00:17.385
Well, I invite you to turn again to wherever we were, Jude.

00:19.409 --> 00:24.338
Let's remind ourselves of a little of this letter beginning in verse 17.

00:25.890 --> 00:30.314
But you must remember, beloved, the predictions of the apostles of our Lord Jesus Christ.

00:31.395 --> 00:36.760
They said to you, in the last time, there will be scoffers following their own ungodly passions.

00:37.601 --> 00:42.446
It is these who cause divisions, worldly people, devoid of the Spirit.

00:43.347 --> 00:55.058
But you, beloved, building yourselves up in your most holy faith and praying in the Holy Spirit, keep yourselves in the love of God, waiting for the mercy of our Lord Jesus Christ,

00:55.298 --> 00:56.800
that leads to eternal life.

00:57.721 --> 01:10.474
And have mercy on those who doubt, save others by snatching them out of the fire, to others show mercy with fear, hating even the garment, stained by the flesh.

01:11.616 --> 01:25.010
Now, to him who is able to keep you from stumbling and to present you blameless before the presence of his glory with great joy, to the only God our Savior through Jesus Christ our Lord, be glory

01:25.314 --> 01:32.261
Majesty, dominion and authority before all time and now and forever.

01:33.142 --> 01:33.502
Amen.

01:34.883 --> 01:54.322
Father, with our Bibles open before us, we pray for the help of the Holy Spirit to be able to speak, to think, to reason, to understand, to believe, to obey, to apply the truth of your word.

01:54.466 --> 02:15.797
conduct that divine dialogue, Lord, the mysterious dialogue whereby the Holy Spirit is at work in our lives beyond the voice of a mere man in a way that is ultimately unmistakable to the end that Jesus Christ may be increasingly formed in us and that we might live to the praise of His glory, for we ask it in His name.

02:16.679 --> 02:17.019
Amen.

02:19.723 --> 02:24.370
We remind ourselves of the fact that Jude was dealing with the presence

02:24.578 --> 02:33.710
and the influence of certain people whose activities were such that he felt compelled to issue an appeal to those who were his readers.

02:35.131 --> 02:52.754
And however peaceable his readership may be by their nature, however tempted they may be to shrink from the battle, Jude is calling them to enter into the fray and to fight with every fiber of their being.

02:52.898 --> 02:57.526
to contend for the faith that was once for all delivered to the saints.

02:58.608 --> 03:09.367
And we noted in verse 8 that these people had mixed an ugly and a dreadfully harmful potion of moral and doctrinal error.

03:10.368 --> 03:18.322
There's a dreadful mixture and Judas concerned that those to whom he writes will not be deceived into drinking the lemonade, as it were.

03:18.818 --> 03:25.388
so that they do not become imbibers of this dreadful concoction which has begun to flow among them.

03:26.850 --> 03:35.222
And when you read Jude, you find yourself saying, there's certain elements of this that just sound so very much like second Peter.

03:36.044 --> 03:38.668
And I leave you to research that on your own.

03:39.248 --> 03:43.995
But you will remember, I think, that Peter is constantly reminding his readers.

03:44.757 --> 03:48.402
He wants to make sure that they never forget these things

03:48.610 --> 03:56.022
And so he tells them that part of the reason for his writing is to stir them up by way of reminder.

03:57.023 --> 03:58.926
And Jude is very much doing the same thing.

03:59.607 --> 04:03.794
And he's using very vivid language in order to address the problem.

04:05.076 --> 04:16.434
I pay a fair amount of attention to contemporary trends in art, not least of all in architecture and in design, not because I have any peculiar ability in it, but it just interests me.

04:16.930 --> 04:23.259
And so I'm always interested when a certain palette of colors becomes the palette of the period.

04:24.040 --> 04:42.066
And in certain environments, we have found ourselves of late in the gray period or in the beige period, where there is nothing particularly vibrant, there is nothing particularly striking, it's not a time for primary colors, it's just all a kind of blah.

04:42.882 --> 04:55.215
It doesn't really do anything to you, and either affects you one way or another, except perhaps depresses you if you're arriving in one of these long hallways in a hotel late at night, just to be met by a great, enveloping grayness.

04:56.476 --> 05:06.026
Well, there are no muted colors in Jude, and some of us have become good at preaching incidentally in grace, and preaching in beiges.

05:06.666 --> 05:10.130
And we wonder why it is that we're preaching our people to sleep,

05:10.626 --> 05:16.393
It's partly because we're not allowing the genre of the text to determine the way in which we're unfolding the text.

05:17.174 --> 05:29.669
We then turn the vibrancy of Jude's language into a muted language in order to satisfy the concerns of those who desire for us to be, for example, politically correct.

05:30.330 --> 05:36.818
No, the way in which he delivers it to us is the way in which we must deliver it to them.

05:37.026 --> 05:41.571
And so Jude gives us these unmistakable and graphic images.

05:42.813 --> 05:47.858
The reason is he wants the people to be able to recognize these people when they appear.

05:49.140 --> 05:52.063
You know, it's not enough just to affirm things always.

05:52.404 --> 05:55.087
You don't always have to say what is.

05:55.487 --> 05:57.169
You have to also say what isn't.

05:57.189 --> 06:04.978
Because if you only say what is, people will nod their heads all the time, as if to agree with you until you tell them, no, no, no.

06:05.122 --> 06:06.023
You don't understand.

06:06.303 --> 06:08.726
That's not what I'm saying.

06:08.746 --> 06:15.675
For example, at a simplistic level, if you have children or grandchildren, you take them out in the car and you show them, you say, look, do you see the cows over there?

06:16.015 --> 06:17.637
And what noise do the cows make?

06:17.657 --> 06:34.418
Or they go, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo, moo,

06:34.658 --> 06:35.359
That's a horse.

06:36.380 --> 06:39.163
Well, you've got to forgive your grandchildren because you never gave them.

06:39.464 --> 06:41.626
You never told them that a cow wasn't a horse.

06:42.747 --> 06:50.957
So now you've got these strange little creatures that are going to be riding on the backs of cows and milking horses unless you may clear to them that you don't do that.

06:51.498 --> 06:55.062
This one moves, but this one doesn't move because this isn't one of those.

06:55.723 --> 07:01.970
And so Jude is pointing out that there is a graphic difference between genuine believing faith

07:02.306 --> 07:12.057
and the people with fat heads, big mouths, who are like waterless clouds, fruitless trees, reckless reefs.

07:12.077 --> 07:12.698
You understand?

07:12.718 --> 07:20.086
I love you, folks," he says, and I want you to understand this, and you need to have it portrayed for you as graphically as possible.

07:20.106 --> 07:24.731
Otherwise, you may fulfill all of these characters, and you may be led astray as well.

07:26.133 --> 07:27.154
If you think about it,

07:27.618 --> 07:33.486
Since these people had crept in undetected as they had, they had crept in undetected.

07:34.307 --> 07:42.358
Either their disguise was superb, or the members of the church were clueless, or a wee bit of both.

07:44.261 --> 07:50.930
For clueless Christians will always be easy prey for clever charlatans.

07:52.252 --> 07:56.978
That's why it is so vital, isn't it, that we teach our people the Bible?

07:57.474 --> 08:02.522
so that they in turn will be able to detect error when it arises.

08:04.425 --> 08:10.013
And for those of you who are youth pastors, can I just say a word to you to get at the business of this?

08:11.235 --> 08:23.954
Your job is not to entertain the average 14-year-old boy or girl, to think up some stupid thing to do on a Wednesday night, as if they are incapable of really getting into the Bible and understanding the truth.

08:24.610 --> 08:37.090
The average kid coming out of the average evangelical church would never be able to explain why they're not Mormon, or why Mormons are not Christian, because you never taught them the doctrine of the Trinity.

08:37.952 --> 08:41.778
You never taught them what we learned today from Philippians 2.

08:42.594 --> 08:52.288
You simply want in Mrs. Jenkins to feel good about the fact that you were being so nice to Sally Jenkins, her little daughter whom she dotes on and understandably so.

08:52.709 --> 08:59.860
And she's a wonderful athlete and she's always at a swim meet and she's doing so very well and she's liked by her friends and you ought to read her Facebook page.

09:00.060 --> 09:02.043
But she doesn't know a thing about the Bible.

09:02.744 --> 09:09.394
And she's about to go to a secular university and they're going to eat her for lunch because you didn't teach her.

09:10.146 --> 09:18.460
And when she said in order to head, like a thing on the back of your car when you're driving in a freeway, well, she's not in like this.

09:18.701 --> 09:19.983
She doesn't know what she's doing.

09:20.904 --> 09:22.507
And frankly, I'm not sure you do either.

09:23.288 --> 09:28.577
So just an encouraging word to the youth pastors while I'm here.

09:30.901 --> 09:33.987
It just can't stop coming out of me.

09:34.027 --> 09:36.050
That kind of encouragement.

09:40.034 --> 09:45.061
Now in the same way, and we've all been at the seminars this afternoon, I poked my head through the window of one.

09:45.121 --> 09:49.006
I stepped into another one, but it got very hot because it was so packed and I left again.

09:49.026 --> 09:51.169
I was too convicted.

09:51.930 --> 09:52.931
I said, oh dear, oh dear.

09:53.872 --> 09:55.575
And now I have to go and preach after that.

09:55.635 --> 09:58.599
And now you're all geniuses because you've all been at the seminars, right?

09:58.979 --> 10:02.103
Transformational preaching, how to get it right and not get it wrong.

10:02.384 --> 10:05.888
Would you like to be up here right now after you're full of all that information?

10:06.449 --> 10:07.350
Let me tell you something.

10:08.572 --> 10:10.034
No one knows how to preach.

10:13.698 --> 10:15.861
It is right that the task should humble us.

10:17.263 --> 10:19.185
It is wrong that it should paralyze us.

10:21.128 --> 10:21.748
We don't know.

10:23.451 --> 10:24.051
We don't know.

10:24.732 --> 10:28.537
When you've read all the books, Sunday hits you again.

10:28.557 --> 10:41.394
Mundy dawns, and another turn of the page, and another blank sheet before you, and another need to bend your knees, and another need to say, help me.

10:43.010 --> 11:00.137
And here, as we do that, I'm trying to teach you how to avoid the difficult parts by avoiding all the section that begins with verse 9 all the way through to verse 60.

11:01.780 --> 11:07.489
I told you already that this is called planned neglect, and it is a wonderful concept.

11:07.549 --> 11:10.674
I learned it early on, and I assign homework.

11:11.394 --> 11:13.256
And that's how I get around it.

11:13.937 --> 11:19.263
That's why I say I'd like you to do this for your homework, come back and tell me what it's about, because frankly, I have no clue myself.

11:20.284 --> 11:23.187
And I'm only being slightly facetious.

11:24.268 --> 11:31.176
Because clearly, it's not possible in the course of two talks to wade your way all the way through this central section.

11:31.196 --> 11:32.497
So I had to make a decision.

11:33.798 --> 11:40.786
Shall I plow around in the vegetation and drag everybody along with me

11:41.122 --> 11:48.393
you know, 4.30, or shall I leave it alone and move to the final section?

11:48.453 --> 11:54.302
Well, if I was going to work this through week by week with a congregation, then I wouldn't skip any parts.

11:55.204 --> 11:57.387
But because I'm not, I'm happy to.

11:58.408 --> 12:01.253
And that's why we're now at verse 17.

12:01.273 --> 12:09.906
1 to 4, contend for the faith, verses 5 to 16, learn from the past,

12:11.810 --> 12:18.657
And in order then to make sense of the present, we need to be reminded of these things.

12:18.757 --> 12:21.260
And so in verse 17, that's what he does.

12:21.340 --> 12:23.062
He says, but you must remember.

12:23.763 --> 12:24.564
You must remember.

12:24.644 --> 12:25.505
Who must remember?

12:25.905 --> 12:29.329
The beloved ones, the agape toy, the loved ones.

12:30.370 --> 12:33.954
I remember that that is exactly what he had done as he began the letter.

12:34.614 --> 12:40.281
So those of you who are called, you're loved by God, and I write to you as my loved ones as well.

12:40.321 --> 12:41.682
You must remember, beloved,

12:42.274 --> 12:48.583
That sense of kindness and tone is very important, although I may be making fun of it in some measure.

12:49.644 --> 12:55.833
Says Jenkins, the work and laborer of a minister should proceed from love to his people.

12:56.934 --> 13:00.519
Love should be the fountain of ministerial performances.

13:01.380 --> 13:05.666
Love is the fountain out of which our ministerial performances emerge.

13:05.727 --> 13:11.154
I think it's in the little booklet by Ian Murray.

13:11.874 --> 13:14.036
that crossed the pulpit of God's love.

13:14.457 --> 13:15.578
I think that's it from memory.

13:15.638 --> 13:36.638
Remember, he says in there that the men who have impacted the church throughout the years have honeyed the church, have honeyed the church with the love of God, who have been consumed themselves by the extent of the love of God, the wonder and mystery of his love, and then out of that fullness and fountain of love, they have sought to encourage others.

13:37.439 --> 13:40.562
And so he says, you need to remember, beloved,

13:40.674 --> 13:42.637
the predictions of the Apostles.

13:43.958 --> 13:47.924
The Apostles had been sent out as sheep among wolves.

13:48.705 --> 13:53.311
They had been promised that the Holy Spirit, when poured out, would lead them into all truth.

13:53.731 --> 14:03.665
They in turn have spoken that truth, and then inscripturated that truth, which has now become the Word of God to us, as we have in the Scriptures.

14:04.966 --> 14:07.730
And so he is concerned that they might remember

14:07.938 --> 14:15.469
that these same apostles of the Lord Jesus Christ pointed out what was going to be our experience.

14:16.750 --> 14:21.898
And we didn't belabor it, but if you remember, Paul was very clear on this.

14:22.358 --> 14:30.290
The Spirit expressly says that in the later times, some will depart from the faith by devoting themselves to deceitful spirits.

14:30.410 --> 14:31.491
That's 1 Timothy 4.1.

14:32.332 --> 14:34.716
In 2 Timothy, understand this.

14:35.176 --> 14:36.338
There will be those.

14:36.610 --> 14:41.537
who creep into households taking captive, weak-willed women.

14:41.557 --> 14:43.680
That's not a generic description of all women.

14:43.781 --> 14:50.631
It's a description of a certain kind of woman, the kind of woman who is always learning and never able to come to a knowledge of the truth.

14:51.432 --> 14:55.478
And of course, when he took his leave of the Ephesian elders, he reminded them of the same thing.

14:55.858 --> 15:06.354
I know that after my departure, fierce wolves will come in among you and then notice the phrase, and from among your own selves will arise men

15:06.434 --> 15:09.218
speaking these dreadful things.

15:10.940 --> 15:34.354
Well, we ought not to be naive in relationship to this, and that is why, as I say to you, that Jude is very, very careful to make sure that these dangerous characters who are responsible for causing divisions, you will notice, scoffers following their own ungodly passions, they cause divisions.

15:35.266 --> 15:49.279
It's the role of the pastor and the teacher as we understand to edify the saints so that they might do the works of ministry as a result of the work and instruction in the scriptures and the building up of the Holy Spirit that we all might be brought to unity in the faith, right?

15:49.840 --> 15:58.648
So as we are working to see these people brought to unity in the faith, Jude says there are those who creep in among you and their objective is the exact opposite of that.

15:59.609 --> 16:04.594
They are responsible for divisive forces, they're dangerous characters.

16:05.538 --> 16:09.865
That's why, back in verse 12, he describes them as hidden reefs.

16:11.668 --> 16:12.469
Hidden reefs.

16:14.032 --> 16:22.326
Some years ago now in Cleveland, I remember one of our either baseball players or football players or basketball players.

16:22.586 --> 16:32.082
Why don't I just say one of the sportsmen in Cleveland was actually killed out on Lake Erie of an evening?

16:32.802 --> 16:39.450
when a speedboat, growing at dramatic speed, encountered a hidden obstacle in the water.

16:40.911 --> 16:43.775
There was no flag there saying, I am a hidden obstacle.

16:44.015 --> 16:46.718
There was nothing there to say, a word of warning.

16:46.758 --> 16:55.628
No, if your objective is to puncture and to destroy and to disrupt, then you do not put a flag up.

16:55.668 --> 17:00.754
You are a hidden reef undetected below the surface.

17:01.954 --> 17:04.858
That's why he's describing them as waterless clouds.

17:06.321 --> 17:19.501
If you think about a desert region, if you think about the prospect that is there, when a cloud breaks across that transparently blue sky, and people say, it looks like there's a chance that we're going to get some refreshment and some rain.

17:20.763 --> 17:25.370
And it proceeds across the sky and disappears as a waterless cloud.

17:25.390 --> 17:29.176
It held the prospect of refreshment, but there was no refreshment from it.

17:29.196 --> 17:30.738
He said, that's what these people are like.

17:32.162 --> 17:37.668
and their fruitless trees with all the branches, but nothing to show for it.

17:38.810 --> 17:40.271
And then he's very graphic, isn't he?

17:40.572 --> 17:43.034
He tells us exactly what they are.

17:43.235 --> 17:45.097
They are devoid of the Spirit.

17:45.437 --> 17:46.478
That's verse 19.

17:48.961 --> 17:56.670
The sensuality that we addressed last night does not share the same bed as sanctity.

17:58.672 --> 18:00.114
And so when you find that,

18:00.738 --> 18:06.966
It's no surprise when you trace it to its root and you discover these people are actually empty.

18:08.588 --> 18:11.010
So that's the first thing you must remember.

18:11.271 --> 18:12.092
You must remember.

18:12.612 --> 18:19.321
Then secondly, in verse 21, 20 and 21, you must keep yourselves.

18:20.362 --> 18:30.354
But you again, beloved, notice the beloved, building yourselves up in your most holy faith and praying in the Holy Spirit, keep yourselves in the love of God.

18:31.170 --> 18:34.074
Again, you'll find this emphasis in 2nd Peter when you check it.

18:35.576 --> 18:43.668
As we end in a moment or two, we're going to be reminded of the fact that Jude is not in any doubt about the keeping power of God.

18:43.688 --> 18:46.753
But the keeping power of God does not operate in a vacuum.

18:49.557 --> 18:51.440
He keeps those who keep themselves.

18:53.823 --> 18:55.526
Now on to him who is able to keep you.

18:56.728 --> 18:57.369
Keep yourself.

18:58.450 --> 18:59.992
I thought he said you're supposed to keep yourself.

19:00.433 --> 19:01.074
Yes, he did.

19:01.410 --> 19:03.672
But I thought it said that he would keep us.

19:03.693 --> 19:04.233
Yes, he will.

19:05.394 --> 19:06.476
And so you mean it's both and?

19:07.036 --> 19:07.617
Yes, it is.

19:09.219 --> 19:10.840
He keeps those who keep themselves.

19:12.002 --> 19:18.028
In other words, there is positive activity that is required of the believer if they're going to make it to the end.

19:18.048 --> 19:20.211
Do you get that?

19:21.452 --> 19:24.956
We are not those who shrink back in our destroyed, says the writer to the Hebrews.

19:25.156 --> 19:27.078
We're not those who shrink back in our destroyed.

19:27.098 --> 19:27.739
Well, who are we?

19:27.959 --> 19:30.482
We are those who continue to the end and are saved.

19:31.266 --> 19:33.830
The ground of our salvation is in the work of Christ.

19:34.150 --> 19:36.634
The evidence of our salvation is in our continuance.

19:38.537 --> 19:39.959
And that's what he's affirming here.

19:41.341 --> 19:51.977
By means of the history lesson, he has provided the dreadful examples of what has happened and what will happen to those who do not keep themselves in the love of God.

19:53.079 --> 19:57.746
That's why our brothers opening a session for us yesterday whenever it was.

19:57.954 --> 19:59.736
Time runs away, doesn't it, HP?

20:01.137 --> 20:21.216
The challenge of it is so necessary, isn't it, about the nature of our own love life, about the nature of our own desire for Christ and for the Scriptures and for our devotion, so that it doesn't become a devotion to the exercise of our duty, that it doesn't become a devotion even to the privileges of our responsibility.

20:22.277 --> 20:26.060
But they were actually keeping ourselves in the love of God.

20:27.041 --> 20:27.922
What does that mean?

20:30.018 --> 20:31.620
Well, again, I was helped by Jenkins.

20:34.022 --> 20:36.865
Incidentally, when you find somebody who helps, you just use it, right?

20:38.086 --> 20:40.809
I mean, don't disguise it.

20:41.750 --> 20:45.814
You know, don't change three words to try and make it sound like, you know, it's yours.

20:47.055 --> 20:50.999
Because everyone can look it up anyway on the internet and go, oh, look at that.

20:52.460 --> 20:56.084
Frankly, nowadays they're actually doing it while you're speaking, right?

20:56.124 --> 20:58.066
So they're looking it up, going, oh, Jenkins.

20:58.594 --> 21:02.680
So let me tell you, not everything Jenkins said, because we're here at about seven o'clock tonight.

21:03.200 --> 21:07.386
But his practical pointers on keeping yourself in God's love go like this.

21:07.767 --> 21:13.234
Number one, keep yourself in a constant hatred of all sin.

21:14.436 --> 21:17.640
Keep yourself in a constant hatred of all sin.

21:17.700 --> 21:25.010
For as love to sin grows, love to God diminishes.

21:25.858 --> 21:32.526
So I cannot keep myself in the love of God if I'm playing fast and loose with willful sin.

21:33.587 --> 21:42.237
If I'm allowing myself luxuries, privileges that are not those that are to be enjoyed by the child of God, it's straightforward, it makes sense.

21:43.058 --> 21:44.180
What is your favorite meal?

21:44.460 --> 21:52.850
Do you remember as a boy coming home, looking forward, Sunday afternoon, after church, you're going home, you're going to get what your mother makes for you, you can't wait, except

21:53.058 --> 21:55.541
You managed to stop a couple of times on the way there.

21:55.902 --> 21:57.104
You got a stickers bar.

21:57.484 --> 21:58.986
You got a large diet coke.

21:59.347 --> 22:01.490
You decide you're like a bag of chips as well.

22:01.890 --> 22:08.800
And by the time you've finished all of that and you present yourself for lunch and your favorite meal is set in front of you and your mom says, what's up with you?

22:09.541 --> 22:10.722
What happens to your appetite?

22:11.583 --> 22:12.565
I thought you loved this.

22:13.426 --> 22:14.968
I do love it.

22:14.988 --> 22:16.190
You know, well, what's happened to you?

22:17.011 --> 22:20.035
I guess I filled myself up with things that I shouldn't have.

22:21.357 --> 22:22.258
That's exactly it.

22:24.418 --> 22:33.231
Secondly, keeping ourselves in the love of God means keeping ourselves in the delight of the friends of God, in the delight of the friends of God.

22:34.894 --> 22:38.178
Now, we understand that we do not isolate ourselves from the world.

22:38.559 --> 22:40.201
The Bible makes that clear.

22:40.261 --> 22:43.486
The boat has to be in the water, but the water hasn't got to be in the boat.

22:43.887 --> 22:51.638
But there are only few friends you can have in the world in any case, and we want to make friends of the friends of God to help us.

22:52.239 --> 22:54.162
I need people who are godly.

22:55.234 --> 23:02.403
Because McShane, remember, he said that our people's need from us is not our giftedness, it is our godliness.

23:02.423 --> 23:08.511
The great need in our lives that our congregation needs from us is our own practical godliness or holiness.

23:09.232 --> 23:13.617
It's not our giftedness at the end of the day because he can be gifted and ungodly.

23:13.657 --> 23:14.759
That's obvious, isn't it?

23:16.381 --> 23:23.890
And also thirdly, he says that you need to keep yourself then if you're going to keep yourself in the love of God to keep yourself in the delight of the ordinances.

23:24.354 --> 23:25.957
in the delight of the ordinances.

23:27.980 --> 23:29.362
Baptism and the Lord suffer.

23:30.344 --> 23:34.631
The importance of these signs and seals of our relationship with God.

23:34.912 --> 23:38.197
Do you know how many people are just toy with these things?

23:39.359 --> 23:50.738
For whom it is a matter of happenstance, whether they are either baptized in obedience to Christ, or whether they do what Jesus said in remembrance of Him?

23:52.450 --> 23:57.916
You can't keep yourself in the love of God while you avoid the means of grace.

23:59.137 --> 24:04.543
For the means of grace are given to enable us to keep ourselves in the love of God.

24:05.944 --> 24:13.091
And it is when we love the people of God that we keep ourselves in the context of it.

24:13.132 --> 24:16.515
The old coal fires gave the perfect illustration, didn't they?

24:16.835 --> 24:19.378
And we've used it all the way along with our children.

24:19.650 --> 24:48.242
telling them you know if you take a lump of coal and you put it in the fire amongst all the other lumps of coal it ignites as a result of the what's going on around it but if you take it tongs and you take a lump of coal out of the blazing fire and you lay it off on the side of the heart you can just sit there and watch as it eventually goes out grows cold and offers no light and offers no heat and offers nothing at all because it is now become isolated from the context in which they could

24:49.026 --> 24:51.971
Keep your spiritual fervor serving the Lord.

24:54.715 --> 24:57.259
Well, I find this very challenging, and I think you may do too.

24:58.400 --> 25:02.206
How do we keep ourselves as the beloved in the love of God?

25:02.226 --> 25:03.128
Well, look at the verbs.

25:03.568 --> 25:09.678
Building, building yourselves up, building yourselves up in your most holy faith.

25:09.738 --> 25:11.020
It's a present part to sipple.

25:12.101 --> 25:15.186
If you're interested, and even if you're not, it still is.

25:17.538 --> 25:18.479
present participle.

25:18.519 --> 25:20.121
In other words, it's a constant activity.

25:20.141 --> 25:21.362
It's a lifelong activity.

25:21.662 --> 25:22.123
Look at me.

25:23.324 --> 25:23.724
Look at me.

25:24.165 --> 25:25.366
How do you think I got like this?

25:25.566 --> 25:27.588
Huh?

25:27.608 --> 25:28.189
Yeah, exactly.

25:31.232 --> 25:34.095
If you don't exercise, it atrophies.

25:35.556 --> 25:37.038
Faith is like a muscle.

25:37.819 --> 25:39.400
You exercise it, you build it up.

25:40.021 --> 25:41.523
You leave it alone at atrophies.

25:44.085 --> 25:44.946
Some of us,

25:46.018 --> 25:51.223
are absolutely maniacal about physical exercise.

25:51.243 --> 26:02.714
If we were to apply 20% of our devotion to our concern to build ourselves up in the most holy faith, we may discover that we'd be a little more effective.

26:04.155 --> 26:06.597
It's a constant activity to build yourself up.

26:06.697 --> 26:07.918
It's a corporate activity.

26:08.219 --> 26:09.480
It doesn't happen on your own.

26:10.901 --> 26:11.802
We need one another.

26:11.822 --> 26:15.986
That's why it's always good to decide you're going to exercise with somebody, isn't it?

26:16.898 --> 26:21.164
I always need somebody to help me so they can lift up the weights for me.

26:22.305 --> 26:25.009
I mean, I can just go pick up 20-pound weights by myself.

26:25.089 --> 26:28.114
I'm going to have to have someone help me, especially when you're lying down.

26:28.234 --> 26:32.219
It's a dreadful prospect.

26:32.239 --> 26:33.281
You got the point, don't you?

26:33.861 --> 26:36.405
Isn't it great to have someone around to help bear the burden?

26:36.445 --> 26:40.050
Bear one another's burdens as you fulfill the law of Christ.

26:41.026 --> 26:45.633
You start to think about gathering and a thing like this and thinking about, is there a brother here?

26:45.713 --> 26:47.535
Is there a sister here I could build up?

26:47.556 --> 26:49.198
Is there a word that I could bring to them?

26:49.218 --> 26:50.940
Is there an encouragement that I could share?

26:51.341 --> 26:56.829
Is there something that I could do that I would help to build them up, to build them up in their most holy faith?

26:56.869 --> 26:58.011
And you know what I've discovered?

26:58.291 --> 27:05.642
When you make it your objective, when one makes it one's objective to build another brother up, you find that you're building yourself up at the same time.

27:07.064 --> 27:08.466
And it's a crucial activity.

27:09.218 --> 27:15.668
but not only building yourself up in your most holy faith, but also praying in the Holy Spirit, praying in the Holy Spirit.

27:16.429 --> 27:18.573
Boy, there's a phrase for the home Bible studies, isn't it?

27:21.337 --> 27:27.046
So then Mrs. Jenkins immediately puts her hands on and says, praying in the Holy Spirit, I'd like to tell you what that means to me.

27:27.967 --> 27:30.231
You tell her, we don't want to know what it means to you, Mrs. Jenkins.

27:30.271 --> 27:31.212
Just go and make her coffee.

27:31.553 --> 27:32.434
Thank you very much.

27:34.690 --> 27:36.012
We'd like to know what it means.

27:36.312 --> 27:38.835
If you come back with coffee, we might ask you what it means to you.

27:38.895 --> 27:40.657
But not until we know what it means.

27:41.218 --> 27:41.919
What does it mean?

27:42.760 --> 27:44.702
Well, we could have a long discussion on it, couldn't we?

27:45.303 --> 27:46.264
But we're not going to.

27:47.085 --> 27:48.867
When you don't know what to do, you quote Calvin.

27:53.052 --> 27:55.074
So let me quote Calvin.

27:55.094 --> 28:01.842
Such is the coldness of our makeup that none can succeed in praying as he ought.

28:02.786 --> 28:06.230
without the prompting and the power of the Holy Spirit.

28:07.372 --> 28:09.354
You immediately go wrong in a phrase like this.

28:09.394 --> 28:19.207
If you started translated into some strange esoteric private prayer language with God, I don't believe for a nanosecond that that's what Jude has in his mind.

28:19.808 --> 28:27.858
And I'm not concerned about your private prayer language for the moment, but in terms of being true to the text, I think that Calvin is a lot more helpful than that.

28:28.706 --> 28:29.567
How can we pray?

28:29.587 --> 28:31.711
It is the work of the Holy Spirit in our lives, isn't it?

28:31.751 --> 28:32.913
It is by the Holy Spirit.

28:33.273 --> 28:39.543
Again in Romans 8 and our brother read from it so helpfully, it is by the Holy Spirit that we are unable to cry Abba Father.

28:40.545 --> 28:41.647
Otherwise, what would we do?

28:42.668 --> 28:44.291
And when do you cry Abba Father?

28:44.311 --> 28:46.354
When does your child cry daddy?

28:47.362 --> 28:54.254
Most of the stuff that I've ever heard on that is all about his son's great experience of God whereby now we cry have a father.

28:54.615 --> 28:59.243
Even the songs were written largely that way, but I'm not so sure that's what Paul has in mind.

29:00.525 --> 29:12.626
I think he may have in mind that when all hell it's loose against us, when the evil one insinuates when we know ourselves to be wretched and poor and blind,

29:13.314 --> 29:24.825
Still, when we get to our bedrooms and we fall upon our knees, we may not be able to say much, but we still say, Abba, sometimes that's all we can get out, isn't it?

29:26.607 --> 29:26.988
Father.

29:29.730 --> 29:33.614
Father.

29:33.634 --> 29:41.682
And the Holy Spirit interprets the groanings of our hearts, to cure your mystery, vital,

29:42.274 --> 29:51.965
in keeping ourselves in the love of God, building, praying, waiting for the mercy of our Lord Jesus Christ.

29:57.131 --> 30:00.175
Again Romans 8 reminds us that we groan, don't we?

30:01.136 --> 30:06.703
We groan as we wait for the redemption of our bodies, the whole creation groans and we groan.

30:08.605 --> 30:09.586
We don't moan

30:10.818 --> 30:11.939
Well, we do, actually.

30:11.979 --> 30:14.562
We're not supposed to be moaning, but we're allowed to be groaning.

30:15.643 --> 30:16.424
For we're waiting.

30:17.725 --> 30:18.486
We're watching.

30:18.746 --> 30:19.467
We're waiting.

30:20.027 --> 30:20.748
We're hoping.

30:21.368 --> 30:21.989
We're praying.

30:23.110 --> 30:26.253
Waiting for the mercy of our Lord Jesus Christ that leads to eternal life.

30:26.514 --> 30:27.134
What does that mean?

30:27.154 --> 30:28.636
I thought we were brought to eternal life.

30:28.676 --> 30:30.958
I thought eternal life was a present experience.

30:31.018 --> 30:31.759
Of course it is.

30:32.179 --> 30:39.186
But we're looking for that great finale in the mercy and goodness of God.

30:40.034 --> 30:52.351
You must remember and then you must make sure that you are keeping yourselves and then to others, show mercy.

30:53.112 --> 30:57.919
So keep yourselves and have mercy on others.

30:57.979 --> 31:01.344
That's the phrase there in verse 23, to others, show mercy.

31:03.187 --> 31:08.434
So the winsomeness and the tenderness of Jude, which we have tried to point out

31:09.026 --> 31:13.012
extends beyond the ranks of those who are doing well.

31:15.095 --> 31:15.456
All right?

31:15.817 --> 31:22.547
That his tenderness and his winsomeness extends beyond the students who are just doing well in the class.

31:23.529 --> 31:31.761
And he wants to make sure that those who are under his tutelage will adopt the same perspective in the encouragement of those who are around them.

31:32.342 --> 31:37.330
It's akin to the emphasis of Paul, isn't it, where he says in Galatians 6,

31:37.442 --> 31:46.074
that the person who has fallen into disrepute and disrepair should be restored, restore him in a spirit of gentleness.

31:47.476 --> 31:58.692
He says the same thing in 2 Timothy where he is urging Timothy to make sure that he cares for his flock and he says that the Lord's servant should be gentle, he should correct his opponents with gentleness.

32:00.514 --> 32:02.657
Now, what are we to assume here?

32:02.717 --> 32:06.002
That Jude having spoken so forcibly

32:06.274 --> 32:22.919
Using these graphic metaphors, is he now, as he's moving towards the end of his letter, having described these people as ungodly, hidden reefs, waterless springs, rootless trees, fruitless trees, and so on, is he now having a spirit of remorse and changing his tune?

32:24.461 --> 32:30.109
Is he now deciding that he's going to wink at the very sins and errors that he has just described and condemned?

32:31.431 --> 32:33.234
No, clearly no.

32:34.530 --> 32:45.324
He is rather urging those who are convinced to be used in the lives of those who are not convinced.

32:46.745 --> 33:03.026
It's specifically those who doubt, specifically those who are playing with fire and to make sure that in seeking to pull the people out of the pit that they themselves are not pulled into the pit.

33:03.970 --> 33:05.532
Let me give you just a cross-reference.

33:05.853 --> 33:08.456
If you've never preached on this passage, I think you will enjoy it.

33:09.037 --> 33:13.083
And if you have, then maybe you should preach on it again.

33:13.143 --> 33:16.748
But for homework, you do Jeremiah chapter 38.

33:17.609 --> 33:19.913
Jeremiah chapter 38, you need to turn to it now.

33:20.253 --> 33:22.737
Jeremiah is thrown in the pit, remember, by his enemies.

33:23.798 --> 33:32.050
And a really nice guy called Ebed Millech, the Ethiopian unit, decided he was going to go and get him out.

33:32.578 --> 33:34.461
And he asked the king if he could do that.

33:34.561 --> 33:35.282
And they said, yes.

33:35.723 --> 33:37.706
And so he decided he was going to go there.

33:37.826 --> 33:42.533
And the record tells us that poor old Jeremiah have sunk down into the pit.

33:42.553 --> 33:43.615
There was no water in it.

33:43.655 --> 33:45.217
He was being sucked up by the mud.

33:45.698 --> 33:47.601
And he'd been left there to die from hunger.

33:49.424 --> 33:52.428
And Ibed Milik took a number of men with him.

33:52.869 --> 33:59.559
And he made a little detour to a wardrobe in the storehouse.

33:59.579 --> 34:00.441
Well, wait a minute.

34:00.481 --> 34:01.362
The guy's in a pit.

34:01.954 --> 34:04.356
Why are we going to the storehouse?

34:04.376 --> 34:05.417
Why are we going to the wardrobe?

34:05.437 --> 34:08.520
Ebad Milik says, trust me, I know what I'm doing.

34:09.561 --> 34:10.902
We're going to get some stuff in here.

34:11.863 --> 34:12.984
And what did they get in there?

34:13.565 --> 34:18.710
They got old rags and worn out clothes.

34:18.730 --> 34:21.653
So the people must have said, this is fantastic.

34:21.673 --> 34:23.895
Jeremiah is in the pit.

34:24.395 --> 34:29.600
Ebad Milik is going to get him out the pit and apparently is important for him to carry all this stuff with him.

34:30.341 --> 34:31.762
And then it all dawned on them.

34:34.850 --> 34:43.019
Then Ibed Meelik, the Ethiopian said to Jeremiah, Jeremiah would throw you down a rope.

34:43.039 --> 34:43.400
Okay.

34:45.001 --> 34:50.508
And be careful because we're just going to throw a bunch of old rags and clothes down as well.

34:52.370 --> 34:52.750
Okay.

34:54.252 --> 34:59.598
And Jeremiah presumably looking up says, okay, I got the rope and I've got the stuff.

34:59.618 --> 35:00.459
What do you want me to do?

35:01.000 --> 35:03.122
Ibed Meelik says, what I want you to do

35:03.362 --> 35:10.492
is to take the rags and the clothes and put them underneath your armpits.

35:10.512 --> 35:23.492
And once you've got them underneath your armpits, then put the rope under your armpits, but make sure that the ropes and the rags are there to protect the rope, to protect your armpits from the ropes, because when we pull you out, we don't want to hurt you.

35:25.094 --> 35:27.057
When we pull you out, we don't want to burn you.

35:28.259 --> 35:30.642
When we pull you out, we don't want to scar you.

35:31.426 --> 35:33.209
We want to bring you out firmly.

35:33.269 --> 35:34.952
We want to bring you out safely."

35:35.593 --> 35:36.975
It's a wonderful metaphor.

35:37.015 --> 35:38.377
I think it fits here.

35:38.457 --> 35:39.479
I don't know if you agree.

35:40.360 --> 35:51.739
Make sure when you go to those who doubt that you go with gentleness, make sure that you go to those who are playing with fire, and make sure that when you go to hold them out, you don't rip their arms off in doing it.

35:52.580 --> 35:53.782
And some of us are perfect.

35:54.002 --> 35:56.306
That's just our ammo, isn't it?

35:56.770 --> 35:57.692
I put the ropes down.

35:57.732 --> 35:58.954
So what if your arms come off?

35:59.074 --> 36:00.256
Get up and get out of there.

36:00.677 --> 36:04.042
Then there's others always like, oh no, we're not going to pull you.

36:04.483 --> 36:07.869
No, we're just going to throw some rags down for you.

36:08.350 --> 36:14.180
And you can maybe rub yourself a little bit and have a great evening, Jeremiah.

36:14.801 --> 36:16.504
We don't want to interfere with you.

36:16.604 --> 36:18.347
And we know your money down there.

36:18.407 --> 36:22.674
And I just give yourself a bye-bye.

36:24.994 --> 36:26.316
That's why we need one another.

36:26.336 --> 36:28.619
It's the guy with the robes going, don't talk a lot of rubbish.

36:29.079 --> 36:32.704
And the person with the rags is going, don't you rip the guy's arms off of that rope?

36:34.266 --> 36:35.167
Well, what are we going to do?

36:35.928 --> 36:38.391
We're going to do exactly what Jude says has to happen here.

36:39.353 --> 36:40.815
Keep yourselves at the love of God.

36:40.835 --> 36:42.096
Wait for the mercy of the Lord.

36:42.176 --> 36:44.279
Mercy there was great and grace was free.

36:44.559 --> 36:50.067
The mercy that has been extended to you by the Lord Jesus is the mercy that you are to extend to others.

36:50.407 --> 36:52.690
So have mercy on those who doubts.

36:54.690 --> 37:00.579
You see, some of us, when we get verse three going, the contending verb, you know, we're contending.

37:01.621 --> 37:08.491
We can get so good at that that we create an environment in which it is virtually impossible for people to give voice to even a question.

37:09.753 --> 37:11.896
We create an environment where nobody can ask anything.

37:12.938 --> 37:18.066
Because we're so busy saying, wait a minute, you sound like a hidden reef to me.

37:19.328 --> 37:19.969
What did you say?

37:19.989 --> 37:23.474
It looks like a fruitless tree.

37:24.130 --> 37:30.460
No, we've got to be prepared to recognize, if we're going to do pastoral ministry, there are people who doubt.

37:32.904 --> 37:34.487
They have misunderstandings.

37:35.208 --> 37:36.410
They have questions.

37:37.672 --> 37:41.017
They are towing with sin.

37:41.037 --> 37:42.640
They need to be snatched.

37:47.568 --> 37:49.010
Snatch them out of the fire.

37:49.538 --> 37:51.441
Again, to others show mercy.

37:51.862 --> 37:55.126
Some, the intervention is going to have to be just like that.

37:55.507 --> 38:01.296
It's going to have to be like the commanders going in, getting the people, hauling them out.

38:01.596 --> 38:03.279
We'll deal with all the other stuff later.

38:04.020 --> 38:05.722
But that's not the key for everything.

38:06.724 --> 38:08.987
So you've got this wonderful combination.

38:09.048 --> 38:15.938
So Thomas Manson, when a fire is kindled in a city, we do not say, yonder is a great fire.

38:16.739 --> 38:18.642
I pray God, do no harm.

38:19.394 --> 38:26.443
In times of public defection, we are not to retain lectures of contemplative divinity.

38:28.265 --> 38:32.331
In a time of public defection, we do not read them lectures.

38:34.133 --> 38:35.655
Help me, I'm drowning.

38:38.038 --> 38:44.466
Well, let me just read to you a book that I read recently about how to do the butterfly stroke.

38:46.594 --> 38:47.715
No, you didn't understand.

38:47.735 --> 38:49.077
I said, I did.

38:54.383 --> 38:56.806
Mercy, combined with hatred.

38:56.927 --> 38:57.908
It's interesting, isn't it?

38:58.348 --> 39:02.854
Show mercy with fear, hating, even the garment stained by the flesh.

39:04.035 --> 39:09.682
The juxtaposition of language is a picture of cleansing and forgiveness and transformation.

39:10.434 --> 39:27.525
Remember in Revelation 7, when you have this amazing picture of the folks that are gathered there, I looked and there was this great company of people from every nation and tribe and language and one of the elders addressed me and said, who are these clothes and white robes and where have they come from?

39:27.585 --> 39:30.390
And I said, these are the ones coming out of the great tribulation.

39:30.710 --> 39:34.898
They've washed their robes and made them white in the blood of the land.

39:35.138 --> 39:39.044
in an old hymn from Scotland that begins with harps and with vials.

39:39.405 --> 39:50.863
There stands a great throng in the presence of Jesus to sing this new song unto him who has loved us and washed us from sin unto him be the glory forever on end."

39:51.183 --> 39:57.653
And the second verse goes, all these once-where sinners defiled in his sight.

39:58.515 --> 40:03.122
Now, arrayed in pure garments in praise they unite.

40:05.218 --> 40:21.237
I spoke with somebody in the afternoon hours by telephone, coming back from the hospital where he's had surgery, a man who has been on our prayer list in our elders' meetings for at least seven years.

40:23.941 --> 40:34.994
And he called to say that the prayers of the people of God, on the one hand mercy, on the other hand, forcefulness, the pulling of the rope,

40:35.650 --> 40:39.555
The kindness of the rags have brought him to repentance.

40:42.358 --> 40:44.921
That is what Jude is talking about.

40:46.603 --> 40:53.572
Not that he feels a little better about the fight that he's a sinner, but that he's had a change of heart, a change of mind, a change of direction.

40:56.075 --> 41:05.426
Loved ones, we cannot show an approach to these things that lowers the standards of God in relationship to this.

41:05.698 --> 41:11.746
There's a great notion abroad that, you know, if you just lower the standards of God, then people will repent more.

41:12.788 --> 41:16.253
Now, that's to love the clothing and to hate the sinner.

41:17.354 --> 41:20.218
We're supposed to love the sinner and hate the clothing.

41:21.360 --> 41:23.903
You must remember, keep yourselves to others show mercy.

41:24.204 --> 41:31.954
And finally, as it finishes in the great affirmation of 24 and 25, to God be the glory.

41:33.176 --> 41:34.738
Jude ends where he began.

41:35.682 --> 41:39.568
reminding his readers that they can have absolute confidence in the keeping power of God.

41:40.490 --> 41:54.772
After all, it's God who called them, it's God who loves them, it's God who keeps them, and therefore he is able to keep them from falling, able to keep you from falling, able to keep you from falling.

41:56.034 --> 41:58.618
I testify to that today, don't you?

41:59.820 --> 42:00.100
I do.

42:02.003 --> 42:03.666
When I think of my teenage life,

42:06.146 --> 42:12.175
being in the homes of some of my kid friends when their parents had gone off to Spain or wherever it was.

42:13.518 --> 42:26.277
When I think of all that was part and parcel of those days, that God in His mercy has kept me and still keeps me, I lift up my eyes to the hills.

42:27.199 --> 42:28.401
Where does my help come from?

42:29.442 --> 42:34.290
My help comes from the Lord who made heaven and earth, not only

42:34.562 --> 42:39.830
Is he able to keep us from falling, but to present as blameless, blameless?

42:42.454 --> 42:51.828
I didn't get many A's, a couple of B pluses, the odd A, but this is fantastic.

42:52.909 --> 42:58.498
The righteousness of God, straight A's for Jesus' sake.

43:00.280 --> 43:01.362
Do you ever be into Augusta?

43:03.426 --> 43:06.130
You're not allowed to eat in the dining room if you don't wear the jacket.

43:07.392 --> 43:09.415
That's tough because I don't have one of those jackets.

43:11.218 --> 43:13.020
Somebody's going to have to let me wear theirs.

43:14.102 --> 43:14.963
Then I can go in.

43:16.465 --> 43:17.587
That's the story, isn't it?

43:18.709 --> 43:22.314
A righteousness which God requires if wherever to stand before Him.

43:23.316 --> 43:27.482
A righteousness which God achieves in the atoning death of His Son.

43:28.644 --> 43:33.010
A righteousness which God declares in the story of the gospel.

43:33.730 --> 43:38.317
and a righteousness which God bestows on all who trust in Him.

43:40.160 --> 43:41.482
You see, that is very good.

43:42.463 --> 43:43.665
Where did you get that?

43:45.307 --> 43:46.849
John stopped.

43:49.594 --> 43:51.516
A righteousness that God requires.

43:52.638 --> 43:54.601
A righteousness that God achieves.

43:55.342 --> 43:57.345
A righteousness that God declares.

43:58.006 --> 44:00.690
And a righteousness that God bestows.

44:01.250 --> 44:04.635
That's how any of us will be able to stand before him.

44:05.116 --> 44:09.924
Bold, I will stand in that great day for who ought to my charge, shall we?

44:14.431 --> 44:22.764
Glory, majesty, dominion, authority, before all time and now and forever.

44:24.908 --> 44:26.450
That's pretty solid close.

44:30.370 --> 44:32.853
my dear brothers and sisters in Christ.

44:34.555 --> 44:40.141
I don't know about you, but I relish the privilege of being alive at this moment in history.

44:41.903 --> 44:49.251
The challenges that appear daunting are opportunities for us to show again the power of God.

44:51.133 --> 44:53.395
Their reminder too is of our great need of God.

44:54.657 --> 44:59.442
If we're going to be kept, if we're going to be continuing, if we're going to make sure that like

44:59.682 --> 45:01.704
Jude says, we get all the way to the end.

45:02.485 --> 45:05.668
We find ourselves saying, you know, I need God every hour of every day.

45:08.151 --> 45:12.475
I think it was 1893 or around that time when the world's fair was in Chicago.

45:14.097 --> 45:16.840
Moody did a big evangelistic outreach of the world's fair.

45:18.001 --> 45:26.610
And at the end of the day, when they had engaged in their endeavors, they would come together and sort of debrief from the day.

45:27.810 --> 45:30.453
They ended every day with prayer and with a song.

45:32.434 --> 45:39.421
And on this particular evening, the song that they sang was, I need the every hour most gracious Lord and so on.

45:40.662 --> 45:46.548
An English evangelist called Henry Varley was visiting and had been present at the events.

45:47.709 --> 45:55.336
And as they concluded the song, he said, Dwight, I'm not so sure about that song.

45:56.057 --> 45:57.298
Why is that said Moody?

45:58.018 --> 46:02.785
Well, he said, I don't think it is comprehensive enough, he said.

46:04.168 --> 46:06.010
Because I don't just need him every hour.

46:06.030 --> 46:08.254
I need him every moment.

46:11.319 --> 46:18.850
In the room was a man called Daniel Webster Whittle, known affectionately as D.W. Whittle.

46:20.232 --> 46:23.858
And unlike HB Charles, who has no name,

46:26.114 --> 46:28.096
Because HB doesn't stand for anything.

46:29.377 --> 46:36.384
Although my name for Dr. Charles is now Henry Billingsgate Charles.

46:40.789 --> 46:44.553
And henceforth I will address him as such.

46:44.573 --> 46:47.155
But D.W. Whittle actually had a name.

46:48.377 --> 46:50.359
And his name was Daniel Webster Whittle.

46:50.379 --> 46:53.682
And those of you who are civil war buffs will be interested in that.

46:54.466 --> 46:58.371
If you're not civil war buffs, you don't know what I'm talking about, so you needn't worry about it.

46:58.892 --> 47:04.280
But D. W. Whittle, on the strength of that conversation, went up to his bedroom and he thought about it.

47:05.081 --> 47:09.647
He thought about the fact that the song says, I need the every hour, and Varley says I need him every moment.

47:09.988 --> 47:15.075
And he took out a piece of paper and he wrote down, moment by moment, I'm kept in his love.

47:16.216 --> 47:19.140
Moment by moment, with power from above.

47:20.182 --> 47:23.186
Looking to Jesus, till glory doth shine.

47:24.066 --> 47:45.308
moment by moment, O Lord, I am thine, and then never a trial that he is not there, and never a burden that he cannot bear, and never a sorrow that he doesn't share, because moment by moment I am under his care.

47:46.849 --> 47:51.474
And the care of God for the pastors and shepherds of the flock

47:52.514 --> 48:12.956
is a care that is to extend to those who are our sheep and our lambs, so that we might convey to them the mercy and the love and the goodness and the intervention of God that together we might follow hard after him.

48:15.399 --> 48:21.906
While gracious God help us to this end, we pray, on our best day we are unprofitable servants,

48:23.074 --> 48:24.015
when we've done all.

48:25.818 --> 48:30.104
We realize again and again how dependent we are upon you.

48:30.184 --> 48:33.608
And yet we thank you that you choose to use the likes of us.

48:34.870 --> 48:35.811
It's quite remarkable.

48:35.851 --> 48:37.293
We never cease to marvel at it.

48:38.735 --> 48:52.434
And I pray that you will help us then as we ponder these truths as they are coalescing with the other studies and our considerations of these days so that we might

48:53.250 --> 49:06.208
keep ourselves in the love of God, and that we might rejoice in the fact that all authority and dominion and power and grace are poured out upon us in and through the name of the Lord Jesus Christ.

49:07.470 --> 49:16.562
And for His sake we pray, Amen.

